---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Collisional Ring Galaxies - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Collisional Ring Galaxies</h1>
        
        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Collisional Ring Galaxies</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Merger product</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Frequency:</th>
                    <td>~0.01% of all galaxies</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Lifetime:</th>
                    <td>~100-300 Myr</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Formation:</th>
                    <td>Head-on galaxy collision</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Example:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Cartwheel_Galaxy" text="Cartwheel Galaxy" /></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Related:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Ring_Galaxies" text="Ring Galaxies" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Mergers" text="Galaxy Mergers" /></td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Collisional ring galaxies</strong> are a rare class of galaxies formed through head-on collisions between a smaller "bullet" galaxy and a larger disk galaxy. They represent one of the most spectacular examples of <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Interactions" text="galaxy interactions" /> and provide unique insights into collision dynamics and induced star formation.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Formation Mechanism</h2>
        
        <p>The standard formation scenario involves:</p>
        
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Approach:</strong> A smaller galaxy approaches a larger disk galaxy</li>
            <li><strong>Impact:</strong> Near-central, perpendicular collision through the disk</li>
            <li><strong>Wave Generation:</strong> Creates outward-propagating density wave</li>
            <li><strong>Ring Formation:</strong> Compression triggers star formation in expanding ring</li>
            <li><strong>Evolution:</strong> Ring expands and fades over ~100-300 Myr</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Key Requirements</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Nearly head-on collision (impact parameter < disk scale length)</li>
                <li>Bullet-to-disk mass ratio typically >0.1</li>
                <li>Relative velocity comparable to orbital velocities</li>
                <li>Target galaxy must have substantial gas disk</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-1">Observational Characteristics</h2>

        <h3>Morphology</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Expanding ring of star formation</li>
            <li>Often asymmetric or incomplete</li>
            <li>Ring radius increases with time</li>
            <li>May show "spokes" connecting ring to nucleus</li>
            <li>Clumpy structure, especially at high redshift<sup>[1]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Star Formation</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Intense star formation in ring</li>
            <li>SFR enhancement factor ~10-100</li>
            <li>Blue ring colors from young stars</li>
            <li>Strong emission lines (Hα, [OII])</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Kinematics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Ring expansion velocity ~50-200 km/s</li>
            <li>Complex velocity fields</li>
            <li>Often retain some rotation</li>
            <li>Bullet galaxy may show high relative velocity</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Evolutionary Sequence</h2>

        <table style="width: 100%; margin: 1em 0;">
            <tr>
                <th>Time (Myr)</th>
                <th>Phase</th>
                <th>Characteristics</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>0</td>
                <td>Impact</td>
                <td>Initial collision</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>10-50</td>
                <td>Ring formation</td>
                <td>Density wave propagates, SF begins</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>50-150</td>
                <td>Peak</td>
                <td>Maximum SF, bright blue ring</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>150-300</td>
                <td>Fading</td>
                <td>SF declines, ring expands</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>>300</td>
                <td>Remnant</td>
                <td>Faint, large ring or normal galaxy</td>
            </tr>
        </table>

        <h2 id="section-3">High-Redshift Collisional Rings</h2>

        <p>Recent discoveries with <WikiLink slug="pages/JWST" text="JWST" /> have revealed collisional ring candidates at unprecedented redshifts:<sup>[1]</sup></p>

        <ul>
            <li>Candidate at z=4.0148 (possibly most distant)</li>
            <li>Several confirmed at z>2</li>
            <li>More clumpy than local examples</li>
            <li>Higher SFRs relative to stellar mass</li>
            <li>Some show smaller physical sizes</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>The "Bullet" Problem</h3>
        <p>Identifying the colliding galaxy can be challenging:<sup>[1]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Bullet may be displaced from ring</li>
            <li>Could be hidden behind target</li>
            <li>May be disrupted or merged</li>
            <li>Low mass makes detection difficult</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-4">As Merger Rate Tracers</h2>

        <p>Collisional rings have been proposed as alternative tracers of galaxy merger rates:</p>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Advantages</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Unambiguous merger signature</li>
                <li>Known formation timescale</li>
                <li>Distinctive morphology</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="evidence-against">
            <h4>Limitations</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Very specific collision geometry required</li>
                <li>May be biased tracer of mergers</li>
                <li>Short-lived phase</li>
                <li>Rare events</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-5">Number Density Evolution</h2>

        <p>The evolution of collisional ring galaxy density with redshift is debated:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Some models predict increase with cosmic time</li>
            <li>Others suggest roughly constant formation rate</li>
            <li>Observations limited by small numbers</li>
            <li>Selection effects complicate interpretation<sup>[1]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-6">Contamination in Lens Surveys</h2>

        <p>Collisional rings can mimic <WikiLink slug="pages/Gravitational_Lensing" text="gravitational lenses" />:<sup>[1]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Similar ring-like morphology</li>
            <li>Central galaxy resembles lens</li>
            <li>Blue ring mimics lensed background galaxy</li>
            <li>Requires spectroscopy to distinguish</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-7">Famous Examples</h2>

        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Cartwheel_Galaxy" text="Cartwheel Galaxy" /> - Classic nearby example</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Arp_147" text="Arp 147" /> - Double ring system</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/AM_0644-741" text="AM 0644-741" /> - Large, symmetric ring</li>
            <li>High-z examples from JWST surveys<sup>[1]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-8">Open Questions</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>How does ring formation depend on impact parameters?</li>
            <li>What fraction of head-on collisions produce rings?</li>
            <li>How do rings evolve in gas-poor collisions?</li>
            <li>Are multiple rings possible from one collision?</li>
            <li>What is the true abundance at high redshift?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-9">Future Prospects</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>JWST revealing high-z population</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Euclid_Mission" text="Euclid" /> and <WikiLink slug="pages/Rubin_LSST" text="LSST" /> will find many candidates</li>
            <li>Need better models for ring evolution</li>
            <li>Improved techniques to identify bullets</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-10">See Also</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Ring_Galaxies" text="Ring Galaxies" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Mergers" text="Galaxy Mergers" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Density_Waves" text="Density Waves" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Peculiar_Galaxies" text="Peculiar Galaxies" /></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-11">References</h2>
        <ol class="references">
            <li>Vizgan et al. (2026) - "JWST's PEARLS: A clumpy ring galaxy at z=4.0148" arXiv:2603.11575</li>
            <li>Appleton & Struck-Marcell (1996) - "Collisional Ring Galaxies" Fund. Cosmic Phys. 16, 111</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galaxy_Mergers" text="Galaxy Mergers" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Peculiar_Galaxies" text="Peculiar Galaxies" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Star_Formation" text="Star Formation" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Rare_Objects" text="Rare Objects" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
